Sam's house has an apple tree and an orange tree that yield an abundance of fruit.
Using the information given below, determine the number of apples and oranges that land on Sam's house.

Sam’s house is represented as a segment on the x-axis, with a starting point s and an ending point t.
The apple tree is located at point a, to the left of the house.
The orange tree is located at point b, to the right of the house.

When a fruit falls from a tree, it lands at a certain distance from the tree’s position along the x-axis:
  A negative distance means the fruit falls to the left of the tree.
  A positive distance means the fruit falls to the right.

Task: Given the positions determine how many apples and oranges land on Sam’s house (i.e., within the inclusive range [s, t]).

Function description:
Implement countApplesAndOranges(s, t, a, b, apples, oranges) that prints two integers:
  The number of apples that fall on the house.
  The number of oranges that fall on the house.

Input format:
Line 1: two integers, s and t (start and end of the house).
Line 2: two integers, a and b (positions of the apple and orange trees).
Line 3: two integers, m and n (number of apples and oranges).
Line 4: m integers, distances each apple falls from tree a.
Line 5: n integers, distances each orange falls from tree b.

Output format:
First line: number of apples on the house.
Second line: number of oranges on the house.

Sample input:
7 11
5 15
3 2
-2 2 1
5 -6

Sample output:
1
1

Explanation:
Apples land at positions 3, 7, and 6. Only one apple (at 7) is within [7, 11].
Oranges land at positions 20 and 9. Only one orange (at 9) is within [7, 11].
